<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA24">
<l>viralōṭu vāytōynta veṇṇeykaṇ ṭāycci</l>
<l>yuralō ṭuṟappiṇitta nāṉṟu – kuralōvā</l>
<l>tēṅki niṉaintayalār kāṇa viruntilaiyē</l>
<l>yōṅkōta vaṇṇā vurai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>At the time when, seeing the butter that had moistened [your] mouth and fingers,</l>
<l>the cowherdess fettered [you] close to a mortar, were you not<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Iruntilai has to be analysed as a very early occurrence of a new type of negation that uses the perfective stem and il as a negative infix; further occurrences cf. Po. 34.3, 79.3, Pū. 89.4. While later this type of form is atemporal, here one might wonder whether a past tense is meant. The final -ē has to be read as an interrogative particle.</note></l>
<l>wailing, [your] voice unceasing, [and] thinking [of it], for the neighbours to see?</l>
<l>O you the colour of the rising flood, tell [me].</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
